these specialized modules

95
00:04:30,569 --> 00:04:34,372
was made by a doctor
named Paul Broca in the 1800s.

96
00:04:34,373 --> 00:04:36,708
Broca had heard of a patient
who had no problem

97
00:04:36,709 --> 00:04:38,376
understanding language,

98
00:04:38,377 --> 00:04:41,079
but who struggled
to produce language.

99
00:04:41,080 --> 00:04:42,747
The only thing the patient
could say

100
00:04:42,748 --> 00:04:44,849
was the sound "tan,"

101
00:04:44,850 --> 00:04:46,017
over and over.

102
00:04:46,018 --> 00:04:47,719
He would say tan,

103
00:04:47,720 --> 00:04:50,722
tan, tan, tan, tan, tan, tan,
tan, tan, tan, tan, tan.

104
00:04:50,723 --> 00:04:51,889
When the patient died,

105
00:04:51,890 --> 00:04:53,758
Broca performed
an autopsy on him

106
00:04:53,759 --> 00:04:55,360
and found that
the patient's brain

107
00:04:55,361 --> 00:04:56,961
had damage to a specific part

108
00:04:56,962 --> 00:04:58,930
 of its left hemisphere.

109
00:04:58,931 --> 00:05:00,998
 Broca concluded
 that this brain region,

110
00:05:00,999 --> 00:05:02,934
 now called Broca's Area,

111
00:05:02,935 --> 00:05:05,470
must be important
for producing speech

112
00:05:05,471 --> 00:05:07,839
but not
for understanding speech.

113
00:05:07,840 --> 00:05:10,975
This language deficit
called Broca's Aphasia

114
00:05:10,976 --> 00:05:13,411
still affects hundreds
of thousands of people

115
00:05:13,412 --> 00:05:16,013
who get strokes
in the left side of their brain.

116
00:05:16,014 --> 00:05:18,850
A patient with Broca's Aphasia
can talk,

117
