00:11:11,002 --> 00:11:12,336
-Oh, hello, Michael.
-Nice to meet you.

262
00:11:12,337 --> 00:11:13,437
I'm Derek. How are you?

263
00:11:13,438 --> 00:11:14,939
Would you like
to come in, Michael?

264
00:11:14,940 --> 00:11:16,173
I'm fantastic.
I would love to come in.

265
00:11:16,174 --> 00:11:17,875
Yes. It's an honor.

266
00:11:17,876 --> 00:11:22,012
I wanted to find out what Derek
could teach us about all brains.

267
00:11:22,013 --> 00:11:24,482
So Derek, I'm doing a show
called Mind Field

268
00:11:24,483 --> 00:11:25,816
about psychology.

269
00:11:25,817 --> 00:11:27,418
Do you know psychology?

270
00:11:27,419 --> 00:11:29,754
I do know psychology.

271
00:11:29,755 --> 00:11:31,989
Your brain
is different than mine.

272
00:11:31,990 --> 00:11:33,257
Would you agree?

273
00:11:33,258 --> 00:11:34,825
I would agree, Michael.

274
00:11:34,826 --> 00:11:37,328
-It's different
than my brain, yes.
-Yes.

275
00:11:37,329 --> 00:11:39,430
 It became evident
 very quickly

276
00:11:39,431 --> 00:11:42,466
 that this was going to be
 an atypical interview.

277
00:11:42,467 --> 00:11:44,802
I'm sure you hear
all the time

278
00:11:44,803 --> 00:11:47,438
about how spectacular
your abilities are.

279
00:11:47,439 --> 00:11:49,373
Were you told that
even at a young age

280
00:11:49,374 --> 00:11:52,910
when you first started
to interact with a piano?

281
00:11:52,911 --> 00:11:54,311
I was told at a young age

282
00:11:54,312 --> 00:11:58,249
when I first started
to interact with a piano...

283
00:11:58,250 --> 00:12:00,017
[Michael] Derek has echolalia,

284
00:12:00,018 --> 00:12:02,553
a condition which causes him
 to repeat back words

285
00:12:02,554 --> 00:12:04,088
 spoken to him.

286
00:12:04,089 --> 00:12:06,323
 It's his way
 of trying to understand

287
00:12:06,324 --> 00:12:07,858
 the spoken word.

288
00:12:07,859 --> 00:12:11,195
You can learn music
just by listening to it.

289
00:12:11,196 --> 00:12:15,065
I can learn music
by listening to it, Michael.

290
00:12:15,066 --> 00:12:16,901
[Michael]
 But while Derek may find

291
00:12:16,902 --> 00:12:18,435
 spoken language challenging,

292
00:12:18,436 --> 00:12:22,006
he has no problem communicating
 through music.

293
00:12:22,007 --> 00:12:25,976
[playing jazz]

294
00:12:25,977 --> 00:12:29,046
 There are about seven million
 autistic savants worldwide

295
00:12:29,047 --> 00:12:31,081
 with some level
 of savant skills,

296
00:12:31,082 --> 00:12:36,187
 but Derek is what's known
 as a prodigious savant...

297
00:12:36,188 --> 00:12:39,023
 which means that his musical
 skills are so outstanding

298
00:12:39,024 --> 00:12:41,125
 that they would be
 considered spectacular

299
00:12:41,126 --> 00:12:44,395
 even for highly trained
 neurotypical musicians.

300
00:12:44,396 --> 00:12:46,964
 There are probably fewer than
 a hundred prodigious savants

301
00:12:46,965 --> 00:12:50,100
 in the whole world.

302
00:12:50,101 --> 00:12:51,902
[Alan] Derek Paravicini
 has a musicality

303
00:12:51,903 --> 00:12:54,572
 that I think any performer
 would envy.

304
00:12:54,573 --> 00:12:56,841
What sort of music
do you really love, Derek?

305
00:12:56,842 --> 00:12:58,342
Uh, maybe
pop music or...

306
00:12:58,343 --> 00:13:00,544
-Okay.
-Jazz, Derek?

307
00:13:00,545 --> 00:13:02,947
A bit of jazz, yeah.

308
00:13:02,948 --> 00:13:04,381
[Michael]
 Since he was five years old,

309
00:13:04,382 --> 00:13:07,184
 Derek has been mentored
 by Adam Ockelford.

310
00:13:07,185 --> 00:13:10,187
Through the door.
Well done, Derek.

311
00:13:10,188 --> 00:13:12,323
 [Michael]
 Adam is a music psychologist,

312
00:13:12,324 --> 00:13:14,458
 author, and professor

313
00:13:14,459 --> 00:13:16,360
 at the University
 of Roehampton.

314
00:13:16,361 --> 00:13:19,029
That's your right hand,
now do your left hand.

315
00:13:19,030 --> 00:13:24,435
Go on.

316
00:13:24,436 --> 00:13:26,604
Derek was born very premature.

317
00:13:26,605 --> 00:13:28,305
 Twenty-six weeks,

318
00:13:28,306 --> 00:13:31,141
which thirty-eight
years ago was very,
very premature.

319
00:13:31,142 --> 00:13:32,910
And they didn't
have any equipment

320
00:13:32,911 --> 00:13:34,378
in the hospital for him.

321
00:13:34,379 --> 00:13:36,513
So they rushed him
into the nearest hospital

322
00:13:36,514 --> 00:13:39,083
that had an incubator,
and Derek

323
00:13:39,084 --> 00:13:41,418
wasn't thought able
to survive, and yet he did.

324
00:13:41,419 --> 00:13:43,020
He's such a fighter.

325
00:13:43,021 --> 00:13:45,022
Because of the circumstances
of his birth

326
00:13:45,023 --> 00:13:48,058
and the impact of blindness
and learning difficulties,

327
00:13:48,059 --> 00:13:51,395
his brain developed
in a particular kind of way.

328
00:13:51,396 --> 00:13:54,899
As a little boy, he was
very fascinated by sound,

329
00:13:54,900 --> 00:13:56,233
not being able to see.

330
00:13:56,234 --> 00:13:59,570
And his nanny gave him
this little electric organ

331
00:13:59,571 --> 00:14:01,906
and that was like
a eureka moment for him

332
00:14:01,907 --> 00:14:04,108
and the beginnings
of his music

333
00:14:04,109 --> 00:14:05,242
processing ability.

334
00:14:05,243 --> 00:14:07,344
So things like language,
things like

335
00:14:07,345 --> 00:14:09,380
perhaps understanding
how people feel,

336
00:14:09,381 --> 00:14:12,182
these things are very
difficult for Derek.

337
00:14:12,183 --> 00:14:14,919
And yet his music
is way above average.

338
00:14:14,920 --> 00:14:16,420
Derek's got
an amazingly quick ear,

339
00:14:16,421 --> 00:14:17,521
haven't you, Derek?

340
00:14:17,522 --> 00:14:21,158
-I have, yes.
-If I go like...

341
00:14:21,159 --> 00:14:23,260
or...

342
00:14:23,261 --> 00:14:26,030
or...

343
00:14:26,031 --> 00:14:27,331
He can process
an amazing...

344
00:14:27,332 --> 00:14:29,033
-[Michael] It's like automatic.
-Yeah.

345
00:14:29,034 --> 00:14:30,567
[Michael]
That's impressive, Derek.

346
00:14:30,568 --> 00:14:32,236
Thank you, Michael.

347
00:14:32,237 --> 00:14:34,605
Yeah, no, the response
to pitch that you make, Derek,

348
00:14:34,606 --> 00:14:36,106
is incredibly fast.

349
00:14:36,107 --> 00:14:38,142
We've measured the time
between playing

350
00:14:38,143 --> 00:14:42,313
even a big chord,
say like this one.

351
00:14:42,314 --> 00:14:45,950
And Derek can listen and react

352
00:14:45,951 --> 00:14:48,485
to an eight-note chord
within about 0.4 of a second.

353
00:14:48,486 --> 00:14:52,556
-Wow.
-Derek's sense of pitch
is very unusual.

354
00:14:52,557 --> 00:14:55,326
-It's also known as perfect.
-It is. It is perfect.

355
00:14:55,327 --> 00:14:57,294
 Something like 40% of babies

356
00:14:57,295 --> 00:14:59,330
 born premature
 who lose their sight

357
00:14:59,331 --> 00:15:01,365
 have perfect pitch
 as opposed to

358
00:15:01,366 --> 00:15:04,435
 about one in ten thousand
in the neurotypical population.

359
00:15:04,436 --> 00:15:07,071
 So you can see that

360
00:15:07,072 --> 00:15:08,739
 the impact of not being
 able to see

361
00:15:08,740 --> 00:15:11,375
has a massive effect on
the way the brain develops.

362
00:15:11,376 --> 00:15:14,144
And how does autism
play into this?

363
00:15:14,145 --> 00:15:16,447
Well, autism
is an added factor.

364
00:15:16,448 --> 00:15:19,049
Autism starts at very early
in life, we know that.

365
00:15:19,050 --> 00:15:20,617
And in Derek's case,
of course,

366
00:15:20,618 --> 00:15:22,453
when he came out
of the incubator.

367
00:15:22,454 --> 00:15:25,322
And what autism tends
to do is to give children

368
00:15:25,323 --> 00:15:28,592
this immense focus
on the sheer quality of things,

369
00:15:28,593 --> 00:15:30,394
whether it's a sound or a--

370
00:15:30,395 --> 00:15:32,596
or a color or a scent.

371
00:15:32,597 --> 00:15:34,732
That's the quality
that we all have as babies,

372
00:15:34,733 --> 00:15:38,669
that we experience the world
in this sheer perception.

373
00:15:38,670 --> 00:15:42,506
Now most babies very quickly
come out of that

374
00:15:42,507 --> 00:15:44,141
by 12, 18 months.

375
00:15:44,142 --> 00:15:46,010
They're starting
to categorize things

376
00:15:46,011 --> 00:15:48,645
just to make sense of the amount
of information that's coming in.

377
00:15:48,646 --> 00:15:50,647
So you're born,
and your body is, like,

378
00:15:50,648 --> 00:15:53,384
consuming all
of this sense data raw.

379
00:15:53,385 --> 00:15:56,253
-Yeah.
-[Michael] And then
it learns that's crazy.

380
00:15:56,254 --> 00:15:58,522
 We don't need to process
 every little detail.

381
00:15:58,523 --> 00:16:00,457
 We only need to understand
 what's important

382
00:16:00,458 --> 00:16:03,260
 or relevant,
 and that's enough.

383
00:16:03,261 --> 00:16:05,095
[Adam] It's called
categorical perception,

384
00:16:05,096 --> 00:16:06,563
and that is a much more
efficient way

385
00:16:06,564 --> 00:16:07,698
of processing information,
and of course

386
00:16:07,699 --> 00:16:09,299
that's why
the brain does it.

387
00:16:09,300 --> 00:16:12,036
But autistic children,
they hang on to those

388
00:16:12,037 --> 00:16:13,637
absolute qualities
for longer.

389
00:16:13,638 --> 00:16:16,073
For people like Derek,
and since he's not only

390
00:16:16,074 --> 00:16:19,376
got those fantastically
vivid absolute memories,

391
00:16:19,377 --> 00:16:22,579
he's also learned
the rules of music

392
00:16:22,580 --> 00:16:26,717
but it's built on this--
on this foundation of perceptual

393
00:16:26,718 --> 00:16:32,623
vividness that
we can only grasp at.

394
00:16:32,624 --> 00:16:35,125
[Michael] While most people
 would find it impossible

395
00:16:35,126 --> 00:16:37,394
 to identify all
 of the individual notes

396
00:16:37,395 --> 00:16:39,596
 in a 10- or 20-note chord,

397
00:16:39,597 --> 00:16:42,166
 Derek is able to do
 this with ease,

398
00:16:42,167 --> 00:16:44,334
 which means
 he can decipher more notes

399
00:16:44,335 --> 00:16:46,670
 than he can play at once
 with two hands.

400
00:16:46,671 --> 00:16:48,072
So we could do that.
If I...

401
00:16:48,073 --> 00:16:49,473
Actually, I have--
I have hands.

402
00:16:49,474 --> 00:16:51,175
-We could combine.
-Yes, yes, yeah.

403
00:16:51,176 --> 00:16:54,244
So-- right, so if you play those
two notes with that hand.

404
00:16:54,245 --> 00:16:58,248
-[Michael] Yup.
-And those two with that hand.

405
00:16:58,249 --> 00:17:05,856
And we'll count for it, okay?
One, two, three, four.

406
00:17:05,857 --> 00:17:08,291
-There you are.
-[Michael] What was
all the fiddling?

407
00:17:08,292 --> 00:17:10,094
[Adam] Well, the fiddling
was to make it--

408
00:17:10,095 --> 00:17:12,096
because he couldn't reach them
all at the same time.

409
00:17:12,097 --> 00:17:13,597
-[Michael] Right.
-[Adam] So his--
he was splitting them up.

410
00:17:13,598 --> 00:17:15,699
[Michael] He's just playing--
but they were all--

411
00:17:15,700 --> 00:17:18,836
they were all in there.
He just couldn't all play
them at once.

412
00:17:18,837 --> 00:17:21,838
 But as amazing
 as his musical ear is,

413
00:17:21,839 --> 00:17:25,142
 Derek's cognitive abilities
 are less than rudimentary.

414
00:17:25,143 --> 00:17:26,677
[Adam] Derek, should we do
some more chords?

415
00:17:26,678 --> 00:17:28,645
[Derek] We'll do some
more chords, Adam.

416
00:17:28,646 --> 00:17:31,582
-So can you play this for me?
-[Derek] Yes, Adam.

417
00:17:31,583 --> 00:17:33,584
Ready?

418
00:17:33,585 --> 00:17:36,186
Good. And do you know how many
notes there are, Derek?

419
00:17:36,187 --> 00:17:37,588
-[Derek] I'm not sure.
-[Adam] Have a guess.

420
00:17:37,589 --> 00:17:39,556
How many do you think?

421
00:17:39,557 --> 00:17:41,758
-Is it one?
-[Adam] Yeah,
a bit more than one.

422
00:17:41,759 --> 00:17:44,895
-So there's one.
-One, two, three,

423
00:17:44,896 --> 00:17:48,765
four, five, six.

424
00:17:48,766 --> 00:17:51,401
-[Adam]
Six, weren't there? Right.
-[Derek] There's six, Adam.

425
00:17:51,402 --> 00:17:53,537
[Adam] Good.
Now try this one then, Derek.

426
00:17:53,538 --> 00:17:55,839
Ready and...

427
00:17:55,840 --> 00:17:58,275
[Derek] Is it one note, Adam?

428
00:17:58,276 --> 00:18:00,444
[Adam] No, there are five.
One, two, three, four, five.

429
00:18:00,445 --> 00:18:02,212
[Derek]
One, two, three, four, five.

430
00:18:02,213 --> 00:18:06,283
It is one, two, three,
four, five, Adam.

431
00:18:06,284 --> 00:18:07,551
[Michael] Tell me more
 about how limited

432
00:18:07,552 --> 00:18:10,387
Derek's everyday abilities are.

433
00:18:10,388 --> 00:18:12,756
Derek finds
almost everything

434
00:18:12,757 --> 00:18:16,160
that you or I do without
thinking really difficult.

435
00:18:16,161 --> 00:18:19,663
So self-care,
things like getting dressed,

436
00:18:19,664 --> 00:18:22,332
getting washed in the morning
are tricky for him.

437
00:18:22,333 --> 00:18:24,935
So all those things
that we take for granted,

438
00:18:24,936 --> 00:18:26,837
he finds really difficult.

439
00:18:26,838 --> 00:18:28,338
-[Cynthia] Derek?
-[Derek] Yes?

440
00:18:28,339 --> 00:18:29,640
[Cynthia] We'll have
to clean your mouth.

441
00:18:29,641 --> 00:18:31,909
[Derek] Could you clean
my mouth now, Cynthia?

442
00:18:31,910 --> 00:18:33,644
[Cynthia] Yes.
Can you come to the sink?

443
00:18:33,645 --> 00:18:35,445
[Derek] I can come
to the sink.

444
00:18:35,446 --> 00:18:37,614
 [Adam] And in fact,
 38 years on, we're saying

445
00:18:37,615 --> 00:18:39,416
"Well, does it really
matter if Derek

446
00:18:39,417 --> 00:18:40,751
"can't put his socks
on himself?

447
00:18:40,752 --> 00:18:42,719
You know,
there are other things in life."

448
00:18:42,720 --> 00:18:46,323
And-- and yet when
he touches the piano,

449
00:18:46,324 --> 00:18:47,758
everything's reversed.

450
00:18:47,759 --> 00:18:50,260
So things that we would find
inconceivably difficult,

451
00:18:50,261 --> 00:18:51,728
Derek does it as easy
as breathing.

452
00:18:51,729 --> 00:18:54,198
And if you ask him,
"Derek, how'd you do that?"

453
00:18:54,199 --> 00:18:55,432
he has no idea,

454
00:18:55,433 --> 00:18:57,501
any more than you
or I understand

455
00:18:57,502 --> 00:18:59,636
how we breathe
or how we speak or...

456
00:18:59,637 --> 00:19:01,338
-Yeah.
-It's purely intuitive.

457
00:19:01,339 --> 00:19:13,684
[playing ragtime]

458
00:19:13,685 --> 00:19:15,352
[Michael] In addition
 to entertaining people

459
00:19:15,353 --> 00:19:17,221
with his remarkable abilities,

460
00:19:17,222 --> 00:19:18,855
 Derek offers valuable insight

461
00:19:18,856 --> 00:19:21,291
 to scientists
 who study the mind.

462
00:19:21,292 --> 00:19:24,428
What do you think Derek
is helping us learn

463
00:19:24,429 --> 00:19:26,663
about this thing
in our head?

464
00:19:26,664 --> 00:19:28,599
I think what
Derek's example tells us

465
00:19:28,600 --> 00:19:31,768
is the almost infinite
capacity of the human brain

466
00:19:31,769 --> 00:19:33,770
to not only survive

467
00:19:33,771 --> 00:19:37,241
but thrive in incredibly
difficult circumstances.

468
00:19:37,242 --> 00:19:39,476
And Derek's potential

469
00:19:39,477 --> 00:19:41,545
really was no different
from anyone else's.

470
00:19:41,546 --> 00:19:44,815
There's no one in his family
who were particularly musical.

471
00:19:44,816 --> 00:19:46,683
So in a sense, you could say
that we all have

472
00:19:46,684 --> 00:19:48,885
Derek's potential
when we're born.

473
00:19:48,886 --> 00:19:51,788
But fortunately, of course,
we don't have his disadvantages

474
00:19:51,789 --> 00:19:55,292
and what gave Derek
his massive advantage

475
00:19:55,293 --> 00:19:57,027
is at the cost
of his disadvantages.

476
00:19:57,028 --> 00:20:04,368
[upbeat music playing]

477
00:20:04,369 --> 00:20:06,670
Autism still
isn't well understood.

478
00:20:06,671 --> 00:20:08,305
 One of the many theories
 for the cause

479
00:20:08,306 --> 00:20:10,907
of autistic people's heightened
 sensory awareness

480
00:20:10,908 --> 00:20:13,810
is that it's at least partially
 due to an abnormality

481
00:20:13,811 --> 00:20:15,812
in the brain's left hemisphere,

482
00:20:15,813 --> 00:20:19,349
 permitting a vast amount
 of sensory details

483
00:20:19,350 --> 00:20:21,585
 to enter
 the brain's awareness.

484
00:20:21,586 --> 00:20:25,422
Neurotypical brains may receive
 all the same sensory details

485
00:20:25,423 --> 00:20:29,559
but block them from awareness.

486
00:20:29,560 --> 00:20:32,362
In fact, some psychologists
have even proposed

487
00:20:32,363 --> 00:20:35,299
that all of us
have savant skills

488
00:20:35,300 --> 00:20:37,868
lying dormant in our brains.

489
00:20:37,869 --> 00:20:39,536
And they may be on to something,

490
00:20:39,537 --> 00:20:41,738
because in extraordinarily
rare cases,

491
00:20:41,739 --> 00:20:45,042
people can actually acquire
savant skills.

492
00:20:45,043 --> 00:20:47,744
A very small number of people
have what is called

493
00:20:47,745 --> 00:20:50,614
Acquired Savant Syndrome.

494
00:20:50,615 --> 00:20:52,849
These are people who suffered
some sort of brain damage

495
00:20:52,850 --> 00:20:54,751
as adults and their brain damage

496
00:20:54,752 --> 00:20:57,587
actually unlocked skills
and abilities

497
00:20:57,588 --> 00:20:59,423
that weren't there before.

498
00:20:59,424 --> 00:21:01,858
 Jason Padgett
 is one such acquired savant.

499
00:21:01,859 --> 00:21:04,094
 After a brain injury
 left him with damage

500
00:21:04,095 --> 00:21:05,829
 to his visual cortex,

501
00:21:05,830 --> 00:21:08,598
 Jason started seeing precise
 geometric patterns

502
00:21:08,599 --> 00:21:10,067
 in everything around him,

503
00:21:10,068 --> 00:21:13,103
 which led to an intuitive
 perception of math

504
00:21:13,104 --> 00:21:15,672
 and physics
 that he never had before.

505
00:21:15,673 --> 00:21:17,541
How did you get
a brain injury?

506
00:21:17,542 --> 00:21:19,543
So I was at a karaoke bar,
and as we left,

507
00:21:19,544 --> 00:21:21,378
these two guys
that were in there singing

508
00:21:21,379 --> 00:21:22,713
attacked me from behind.

509
00:21:22,714 --> 00:21:24,715
They smashed me
in the back of the head.

510
00:21:24,716 --> 00:21:25,982
Well, I just heard
this deep thud,

511
00:21:25,983 --> 00:21:27,117
saw a little
puff of white light,

512
00:21:27,118 --> 00:21:28,752
which I later found out
was my brain

513
00:21:28,753 --> 00:21:30,387
bouncing on the inside
of my skull.

514
00:21:30,388 --> 00:21:32,456
I didn't know where I was,
how I got there,

515
00:21:32,457 --> 00:21:33,790
why I was being attacked.

516
00:21:33,791 --> 00:21:35,959
[Michael] So now you
have Akinetopsia,

517
00:21:35,960 --> 00:21:39,996
meaning you see
the world now in frames.

518
00:21:39,997 --> 00:21:42,733
-What does that mean?
-In discreet picture frames.

519
00:21:42,734 --> 00:21:44,768
When I say discreetly,
I mean seeing one picture

520
00:21:44,769 --> 00:21:46,470
and another picture.
So imagine like anybody

521
00:21:46,471 --> 00:21:48,071
watching TV right now,
they can hit pause

522
00:21:48,072 --> 00:21:49,873
and pause again and see
the picture frame

523
00:21:49,874 --> 00:21:51,608
by frame by frame.

524
00:21:51,609 --> 00:21:53,744
It's just like that,
but in real time.

525
00:21:53,745 --> 00:21:55,779
It also makes everything look
slightly pixelated.

526
00:21:55,780 --> 00:21:58,448
So boundaries of objects
don't look curved

527
00:21:58,449 --> 00:21:59,783
like smooth curves anymore.

528
00:21:59,784 --> 00:22:00,984
They look like
they have these tiny

529
00:22:00,985 --> 00:22:02,586
little straight line edges.

530
00:22:02,587 --> 00:22:03,920
Are you seeing me
that way right now?

531
00:22:03,921 --> 00:22:06,456
Yes. So like,
if you're not moving,

532
00:22:06,457 --> 00:22:08,825
it's more like a picture
on a picture on a picture,

533
00:22:08,826 --> 00:22:10,494
so it's not nearly
as profound,

534
00:22:10,495 --> 00:22:12,429
but when something moves
like this,

535
00:22:12,430 --> 00:22:13,764
then it's much more profound.

536
00:22:13,765 --> 00:22:15,165
So after the injury,

537
00:22:15,166 --> 00:22:17,701
you have all these
perceptual changes.

538
00:22:17,702 --> 00:22:20,804
What makes you decide
that you need
to start drawing?

539
00:22:20,805 --> 00:22:23,573
So at the time,
I had no way to describe

540
00:22:23,574 --> 00:22:25,709
what I was seeing
in any terms

541
00:22:25,710 --> 00:22:27,110
except for to draw it.

542
00:22:27,111 --> 00:22:28,779
I started trying
to define things

543
00:22:28,780 --> 00:22:30,947
with triangles
and straight lines.

544
00:22:30,948 --> 00:22:34,684
Geometry is-- to me
is the one thing everything has,

545
00:22:34,685 --> 00:22:37,521
even nothing.
Empty space is geometry.

546
00:22:37,522 --> 00:22:38,722
It just seemed obvious.

547
00:22:38,723 --> 00:22:40,957
I mean, the universe
is math for me.

548
00:22:40,958 --> 00:22:43,527
 [Michael] Are these
 thoughts that you would've
 had before the injury?

549
00:22:43,528 --> 00:22:45,829
No, not at all.
Never even contemplated

550
00:22:45,830 --> 00:22:48,865
this type of stuff and now
I can't stop thinking about it

551
00:22:48,866 --> 00:22:50,167
and I wound up going
to the mall.

552
00:22:50,168 --> 00:22:51,635
So I'm sitting there
eating this sandwich

553
00:22:51,636 --> 00:22:53,170
and I'm drawing,
and this guy next to me,

554
00:22:53,171 --> 00:22:54,871
he says he's a physicist.
And he goes,

555
00:22:54,872 --> 00:22:56,840
"It looks like you're doing
some sort of math there."

556
00:22:56,841 --> 00:22:58,842
And I started telling him,
you know, my ideas.

557
00:22:58,843 --> 00:23:01,111
And he says "It sounds to me
like you're trying to describe

558
00:23:01,112 --> 00:23:03,447
space, time, and limits."

559
00:23:03,448 --> 00:23:05,115
And things that
I didn't understand
what he was talking about.

560
00:23:05,116 --> 00:23:06,850
He goes, "But you're doing it
in layman terms

561
00:23:06,851 --> 00:23:08,919
"and I've never heard anybody
try to do that before."

562
00:23:08,920 --> 00:23:10,220
It turns out
it was integrals.

563
00:23:10,221 --> 00:23:12,456
What I was doing
was integrals and calculus.

564
00:23:12,457 --> 00:23:14,691
You're now pursuing
an education in math?

565
00:23:14,692 --> 00:23:16,893
-[Jason] Yes.
-So would you say that

566
00:23:16,894 --> 00:23:20,464
you're still the same person

567
00:23:20,465 --> 00:23:22,098
who existed
before the injury,

568
00:23:22,099 --> 00:23:24,935
or did you become
a different individual?

569
00:23:24,936 --> 00:23:27,137
I feel like I've
had two different lives.

570
00:23:27,138 --> 00:23:29,573
Before the injury, I didn't have
any background in math.

571
00:23:29,574 --> 00:23:30,974
I didn't even have algebra.

572
00:23:30,975 --> 00:23:32,943
I didn't even know
that you could graph a line.

573
00:23:32,944 --> 00:23:35,846
All I did was party
and chase girls.

574
00:23:35,847 --> 00:23:37,814
It was a very shallow,
you know,

575
00:23:37,815 --> 00:23:40,050
almost blissfully
ignorant life.

576
00:23:40,051 --> 00:23:42,786
Do you think
that these abilities

577
00:23:42,787 --> 00:23:44,488
were always in your brain

578
00:23:44,489 --> 00:23:46,923
and got somehow
unlocked by the injury,

579
00:23:46,924 --> 00:23:49,826
or did the injury
give you something new?

580
00:23:49,827 --> 00:23:53,129
I 100% believe that
we all have this in us.

581
00:23:53,130 --> 00:23:55,031
You know, people think
that I got hit in the head

582
00:23:55,032 --> 00:23:56,867
and just magically
got good at math

583
00:23:56,868 --> 00:23:58,902
but a lot of it
is your brain gets damaged

584
00:23:58,903 --> 00:24:01,538
and you're forced to see
the world differently,

585
00:24:01,539 --> 00:24:02,806
and by seeing the world
differently,

586
00:24:02,807 --> 00:24:04,541
it makes you think
differently.

587
00:24:04,542 --> 00:24:06,843
[Michael] We can learn
so much from divergent minds,

588
00:24:06,844 --> 00:24:08,578
 whether it would be someone
 like Jason

589
00:24:08,579 --> 00:24:10,046
 who developed
 his divergent mind

590
00:24:10,047 --> 00:24:11,515
 from an accident
 as an adult...

591
00:24:11,516 --> 00:24:13,149
Hello, Ashleigh.

592
00:24:13,150 --> 00:24:14,551
[Ashleigh] Hello, Derek.

593
00:24:14,552 --> 00:24:15,852
[Derek] How are you?

594
00:24:15,853 --> 00:24:17,153
[Michael]
 ...or someone like Derek,

595
00:24:17,154 --> 00:24:18,555
 whose divergence came

596
00:24:18,556 --> 00:24:20,090
 from complications
 at birth.

597
00:24:20,091 --> 00:24:21,825
[Adam] One of Derek's
great strengths is working

598
00:24:21,826 --> 00:24:23,860
with other disabled people
and disabled children.

599
00:24:23,861 --> 00:24:29,266
They love him.

600
00:24:29,267 --> 00:24:31,835
Beautiful, Ashleigh.
Well done.

601
00:24:31,836 --> 00:24:33,737
Derek is a hero,

602
00:24:33,738 --> 00:24:35,939
particularly amongst
the learning disabled.

603
00:24:35,940 --> 00:24:38,642
For anyone with severe
learning difficulties,

604
00:24:38,643 --> 00:24:40,243
to have a public life,

605
00:24:40,244 --> 00:24:41,878
to travel
all over the world,

606
00:24:41,879 --> 00:24:43,547
to meet hundreds of people,

607
00:24:43,548 --> 00:24:45,882
to have acclaim
from millions of people

608
00:24:45,883 --> 00:24:47,217
on the internet is--

609
00:24:47,218 --> 00:24:49,052
he's unique
in that perspective.

610
00:24:49,053 --> 00:24:52,222
He's a trailblazer,
but we should never forget

611
00:24:52,223 --> 00:24:54,758
that he's part of a population
that's much bigger

612
00:24:54,759 --> 00:24:57,727
and tends to be hidden away
from society.

613
00:24:57,728 --> 00:25:05,135
[upbeat music playing]

614
00:25:05,136 --> 00:25:07,170
Derek raises
important questions

615
00:25:07,171 --> 00:25:09,272
about the diversity of minds.

616
00:25:09,273 --> 00:25:12,042
Autistic minds
like all divergent minds

617
00:25:12,043 --> 00:25:14,277
are not alien;
they're human minds

618
00:25:14,278 --> 00:25:17,581
and they provide windows
into how we all think,

619
00:25:17,582 --> 00:25:19,616
feel, and behave.

620
00:25:19,617 --> 00:25:22,152
A complete brain science
should be able to account

621
00:25:22,153 --> 00:25:25,055
for all kinds
of minds and brains.

622
00:25:25,056 --> 00:25:27,891
As long as some minds
remain a mystery,

623
00:25:27,892 --> 00:25:30,860
so too will all minds.

624
00:25:30,861 --> 00:25:36,366
And as always,
thanks for watching.

625
